 "prose": "\"Bad instruments,\" Maren says, and makes herself laugh, a short dry sound she barely recognizes. \"Worse weather. You'll get numbers like that on any rock this far out \u2014 the currents chew the lead line before it's halfway down.\"\n\nElias watches her longer than the answer deserves. She holds his eyes and does not blink, and after a moment he nods, slowly, and goes back to his figures as though the matter is closed.\n\nThat night she takes the ledger's last leaf, the one he nearly glimpsed open on the chart table, and feeds it to the stove herself, watching the corners curl before the rest catches. The blank line is ash before it can be read by anyone but her.\n\nBut something in Elias has gone quiet since the soundings, and quiet is not the same as satisfied. He watches the tide tables now the way he used to watch his own instruments, and he watches her too, sidelong, over the rim of a teacup, at every meal they share on the narrow gallery table. He does not ask again. He does not need to. The lie sits between them at every meal like a third, silent guest, patient as the thing below the stilts, and just as unwilling to leave.\n\nOutside, the storm eases toward the kind of hush that only comes after. Maren finds she cannot tell, some evenings, whether he is still gathering soundings, or simply gathering her.\n",
